ITGRIAL
Drug Policy
Needs Revision
During the first two weeks of the new semester, two students
were placed on conduct promotion alter seeking medical attention
It the health center while on “bad trips.” Another student who
was dealing in illegal drugs “voluntarily withdrew" brown the
college at the request of the administration. .
who means displayed poor judgment in their handling or the
ﬁrss two incidents. According to the Student Handbook, the col<
legs recognized “the serious possibility oi damage to the mental
and physical health of (drug) users” By disciplinary students who
visit the Health center with problems sterling from the use or
drugs, the means are discouraging students from seeking medical
attention when their lives may depend upon it.
In the case of the student who took an overcome of messaging,
undefined fellow-students —- rather than seeking immediate medical
attention — administered drugs that seriously endangered the students life, presumably because they shared disciplinary reserves
lions, it should be obvious to the means that disciplinary handling
ol medical problems will only increase the rangers of drug in-
,agreement at Grinnell.
Although professional ethics may require that the details of
rsonal cases handled by the means remain Confidential, the
rely surrounding the promotion incidents is independence. All
engineers of the College community are entitled to know when,
and why, the means discipline students. The college has recognized
similar rights in the past by requiring the disclosure of judicial
council proceedings
in the case of the student dealing In messaging, the means lib
decided better judgment. A student who is so instantly indiscrere
that the means are aware of his drug involvement is a danger not
only to himself, but to the entire community, and it is perhaps
best for all concerned that he withdrew from the college.
The mistakes made during the past two weeks point out the
urgent need for the creation of an adequate drug education program at Grinnell. Such a program will be northwest if it consists
ol nothing more than the governing propaganda plans previously
used to share students away from drugs,
Grindeil needs a drug education program that forestry approaches the psychological, psychological, social, and legal consequences of instrumentation with drugs. It must examine not only
the rangers of drugs, but also their positive potential.
A statement clarllying the college drug policy is expected from
the President next week. He can no longer ignore the many dell«
Gate questions integral to the solution of the drug problem,
Is the college reporting to an in logo parental policy in its
handling of drug cases? Will continued disciplinary actions dis<
courage students from seeking needed medical care? is the drug
policy consistent with other college regulations oi student conduct?
These are only a few of the difficult questions that call for lm<
message answers,
Poor judgment in the past has participated the current drug
problem at Grinnell. Necessity demands a realistic reappraisal of
The situation now. -- M.B., TIT.
 
